{title: I'll Pick Pretty Flowers}
{artist: Wendy Lewis}
{composer: Written by Judith Elaine Pagter}

[G]As I sit here [C]recalling the [G]days of my youth
[D7]Remembering when I was a [G]child
I strolled by the [C]stream where the [G]wild flower grew
And [C]picked pretty [D7]flowers for [G]you
There were [D7]tree locks and [G]violets and [C]silver bells [G]too
[D7]Jack in the [G]pulpit and May apples [D7]too
Don’t [G]worry dear [C]momma I’ll be [G]back in the spring
To [C]pick pretty [D7]flowers for [G]you
I haven’t [C]forgotten those [G]sweet mother dear
To [D7]take time to walk by the [G]woods
Where the hillsides are [C]laden with [G]colors of blue
And [C]pick pretty [D7]flowers for [G]you

Repeat #2
And mom when I’m [C]older I’ll [G]still do the same
[D7]That’s one thing I’ll never out[G]grow
As long as there’s [C]forest and [G]mountain streams filled
I’ll [C]pick pretty [D7]flowers for [G]you
Repeat #2
I’ll [C]pick pretty [D7]flowers for [G]you